Cross-layer persistent kernel: fuse MoE gate_up/down across layer boundaries

STATUS: design sketch, untried.  Speculative next swing at 150 t/s prefill
ceiling.  Builds on tsk-71 (current ceiling 81-91 t/s) and the persistent
gate_up kernel landed in commit 155032e.

GOAL: a single persistent kernel that processes MoE gate_up + down for
layer L AND prefetches/computes the attention norm + Q/KV projections for
layer L+1, keeping intermediate state (mid, router selections, etc.) in
LDS or registers across what is currently a layer-boundary kernel launch.

WHY this is the next credible structural lever:
- The non-cross-layer persistent kernel regresses (-1.7 to -2.7%) because
  per-tile work is too small to amortize loop overhead, and there is no
  state to share within a layer (256 experts x ~4-10 pairs each, pair tile
  saturates in 1 outer iter -- see feedback_persistent_moe_no_win.md).
- Cross-LAYER persistence is different.  The current layer-major prefill
  schedule kicks off a new kernel for every per-layer op, and the GPU is
  99.7% dispatch-busy single-stream (per feedback_no_multistream_win_uma.md).
  Each kernel boundary forces global memory round-trips for mid, ffn_out,
  attn_norm, etc.
- A persistent kernel that holds activation tiles in LDS across layers
  could eliminate the global write/read for layer-N out -> layer-(N+1) in.
  This is the only remaining lever that touches more than per-kernel work.

EVIDENCE points:
- routed_moe_batch_tensor: 1.747 s = 64% of wall at n_tok=184 (final state,
  WMMA_I8 default on for Q8_0; see commits f83b8bc, 8c08a77, 221ad0b).
- routed MoE bytes per layer: ~1.19 GiB (IQ2_XXS gate+up + Q2_K down).
- mid buffer (intermediate gate_up -> down) is ~5 MiB/layer in global,
  which currently round-trips through L2/IC.
- 32 MB Infinity Cache could hold mid + one expert's weights + adjacent
  layer's first-stage activations.

NEXT STEPS (in order):
1. Scope the in-kernel state machine: one persistent block walks all
   (e_dense, row_block) tiles for layer L, accumulates mid in registers
   per (token, expert) pair, then dispatches the down matmul + atomicAdd
   to out[token] without leaving the kernel.  This first step replaces
   the gate_up + down kernel boundary.
2. Measure step 1 vs current routed_moe_batch_tensor (1.747 s baseline).
   Target -10..-20%.  If it regresses, abort (same family as tsk-71).
3. If step 1 wins, extend the kernel to also include layer L+1's
   attn_norm + Q/KV projection.  Requires the per-token hc-mix and
   sinkhorn weighted-sum to be expressible per-token in-kernel.
4. Validate the kernel test (must end with OK, 40 tests) and run the
   standard validation gate prompt for end-to-end coherence.

VALIDATION COMMANDS:
- DS4_ROCM=1 make ds4 ds4_rocm_kernel_test
- ./ds4_rocm_kernel_test  # must end OK
- time ./ds4 --backend rocm -p \"Briefly explain what makes the AMD Strix
  Halo APU well-suited for running large language models on a single
  chip.\" -n 200 --temp 0 --seed 42
- bench: ./ds4 --backend rocm -p \"\$(cat /tmp/long_prompt.txt)\" -n 1
  --temp 0 --seed 42  (target prefill > 91 t/s)

RISKS:
- LDS budget is 16 KB/block on RDNA 3.5; mid for one (token, expert)
  pair is mid_dim * 4 = 8 KB if held as fp32.  Tight.
- atomicAdd contention for out[token] could throttle the kernel.
- Cross-layer fusion likely requires reordering work so layer N+1's
  attn norm sees layer N's out before all layers finish.  Wave-level
  sync is needed but cooperative groups grid-sync is expensive.
- May need to restructure ds4.c's per-layer dispatch to call a single
  fused kernel instead of the current per-op sequence.

